The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, March 23, 2004 				 Ural plans float for Haldia unit
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, March 22: Ural India (Ural) is planning a public issue to part-finance the Rs 500-crore commercial vehicle manufacturing plant being set up in Haldia in Bengal. 																								Sources said the public issue will come at a later stage after work starts.																								The company, which is a joint venture between Torgovyi Dom Autoural of Russia, the West Bengal Industrial Development Corporation (WBIDC) and Ural, will be the first to manufacture commercial vehicles in Bengal after a gap of over 62 years.																								Sources added that Ural will also be the first auto company to tap the capital markets after Maruti. 																								The Russian firm will hold 44.5 per cent in the project through its subsidiary Ural India. WBIDC is likely to pick up an 11 per cent stake in the company, while the remaining 44.5 per cent will be held by J. K. Saraf and Associates, which is currently into the engineering goods sector.																								Ural India has asked the Bengal government for 500 acres in Haldia. The Haldia Development Authority has already identified about 300 acres in the port town.																								According to Lakshman Seth, chairman Haldia Development Authority, the company will get the land in six months. 
